sec.p:
The learning curve quantifies empirically the impact of learning by doing on the production costs of an industry or a firm by considering the investment costs as a declining function of cumulative capacity or cumulative output. Both of these factors are an approximation of knowledge (cf. Argote et al. 1990). In literature, a variety of different functional forms modeling these interrelationship can be found; the probably most common one, however, is the log-linear function to its simplicity and its observed good fit with data. In this case, the progressive decrease is explained by the so-called progress rate given asPR=2-α,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
