				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{ p}_{ F}}=0.0609$$\end{document} in Scenario 1, one can observe from Fig. 13 that this here happens already at pF=0.0328\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{ p}_{ F}}=0.0328$$\end{document}. As the supply of global radiation is higher, the investment costs per unit of power for an equal capital stock here are even lower than for the other two cases. Hence, investments into renewable energy get profitable already at a lower fossil energy price. For this reason, also the indifference threshold curve has shifted to the left. The high mixed solution in Scenario 2 gets dominant at pF=0.0449\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
